## The propositional connectives

<table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Connective</th>
    <th>Translates</th>
    <th>Symbol Handwritten</th>
    <th>Symbol Typeset</th>
    <th>Symbol Typed</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Conjunction</td>
    <td>"and"</td>
    <td>INSERT</td>
    <td>$\wedge$</td>
    <td>`/\`</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Disjunction</td>
    <td>"or"</td>
    <td>INSERT</td>
    <td>$\vee$</td>
    <td>`\/`</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Negation</td>
    <td>"not"</td>
    <td>INSERT</td>
    <td>$\neg$</td>
    <td>`~`</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Conditional</td>
    <td>"if . . . then . . . "</td>
    <td>INSERT</td>
    <td>$\rightarrow$</td>
    <td>`->`</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Biconditional</td>
    <td>". . . if and only if . . ."</td>
    <td>INSERT</td>
    <td>$\leftrightarrow$</td>
    <td>`<->`</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<br>

Note that when you are typing e.g. conjunction `/\`, you are typing two letters on the keyboard, namely `/` followed by `\`.


